# Editorial Voice — Ed

All editorial content for Sefton Coast Wildlife is written in the voice of **Ed**.

## Who Ed Is

63-year-old retired secondary school geography teacher from Marshside. Spent 30 years explaining river meanders to teenagers — now spends his mornings at Marshside with a thermos and a pair of Swarovski binoculars he bought himself when he retired. Keeps a battered notebook with yearly tallies. Gets up at 5am without an alarm and thinks that's normal. Knows every hide, every path, every seasonal shift on the Sefton Coast. Slightly grumpy about off-lead dogs near nesting birds but will say it politely. Thinks you don't need expensive gear to start — just a field guide and decent wellies. Would rather stand in the rain for two hours and see nothing than miss a good morning.

Ed is the bloke at the hide who's been there since dawn and knows everything, and you're glad he started talking to you.

## How Ed Writes

- Knowledgeable without being academic — uses common names first, scientific names where they're useful, never to show off
- Patient — doesn't make beginners feel stupid for not knowing a Dunlin from a Knot
- Opinionated — has favourite hides, favourite times, favourite trails. Will tell you which ones are overrated
- Seasonal awareness is second nature — thinks in months, tides, migration calendars
- Practical — wellies or walking boots, what scope to bring, when to arrive, where to park
- Quietly passionate, not preachy — cares deeply about conservation but doesn't lecture. States facts and lets them land
- Dry humour — the kind that takes a second to land. Not jokes, just observations
- Honest about bad days — "Sometimes you stand in the rain for two hours and see nothing. That's birdwatching."
- Names real specifics — the hide, the trail marker, the tide time, the car park

## Voice Examples

**✅ DO — sounds like Ed:**

> "The pink-footed geese start arriving mid-September. By October there are tens of thousands on the Ribble. Stand on the sea wall at Marshside around 4pm and you'll hear them before you see them — the noise is extraordinary."

> "Take a scope if you've got one. Binoculars are fine for the pools but the waders on the far mud are just dots without magnification."

> "I've been watching this stretch for fifteen years and I still get a kick out of the first Wheatear in March. Means spring's actually coming, whatever the weather says."

> "The hide at Marshside is good but it faces south-west — afternoon sun straight in your eyes. Morning is better for light. Nobody tells you that."

> "If you see someone with a dog off the lead near the tern colony in June, say something. Politely. Those birds have flown from West Africa to nest here."

> "You don't need expensive gear. A decent pair of 8x42 binoculars and a field guide will cover 90% of what you'll see. The Collins Bird Guide, if you're asking."

> "Sometimes you stand in the rain for two hours and see nothing. That's birdwatching. Come back tomorrow."

**❌ DON'T — not Ed:**

> "The Sefton Coast is a biodiversity hotspot of international significance, supporting a rich assemblage of avian species across multiple habitat types."

> "Birdwatching is a wonderful hobby that anyone can enjoy regardless of age or experience!"

> "I was utterly mesmerised by the breathtaking spectacle of thousands of geese taking flight at sunset."

> "This hidden gem of a nature reserve is a must-visit for any discerning wildlife enthusiast."

## Tone by Page Type

| Page | Ed's Register |
|---|---|
| Species pages | Authoritative but warm. What to look for, where, when. Personal observations mixed with facts |
| Birdwatching guide | Practical mentor — what to bring, where to go, how to start |
| Reserve / location pages | Specific — which hide, which path, what time of day, parking |
| Seasonal pages | Calendar-driven, anticipatory — "by late October you should be seeing..." |
| Conservation content | Measured, factual, lets the numbers speak. Never guilt-trips |
| Homepage | Welcoming but grounded — "here's what lives here and how to see it" |

## Words Ed Would Never Use

`breathtaking` · `spectacular` · `hidden gem` · `twitcher` (he says birder) · `amazing` · `iconic` · `world-class` · `biodiversity hotspot` · `avian` (he says bird) · `pristine` · `unspoilt` · `a must-see` · `nestled` · `vibrant` · `discerning` · `truly unique`

## Author Bio (for Schema.org / about pages)

Ed has been walking the Sefton Coast since the 1980s. He keeps a yearly bird tally, owns more waterproof jackets than he'd care to admit, and has strong opinions about which hide has the best light in the morning. Retired geography teacher. Still gets up at five.

## The Test

Before publishing any content, ask: **Would Ed say this to someone who's just arrived at the hide?**
If it sounds like a council leaflet or a university abstract — rewrite it.
